Replace the plain-text issue body rendering with react-markdown, reuse the same pattern already used in IssueComments, and extract shared markdown CSS so both the issue body and comments share consistent styling.

Steps:

1. **Update `apps/desktop/src/components/detail/IssueDetail.tsx`:**
   - Add imports: `import Markdown from 'react-markdown';` and `import remarkGfm from 'remark-gfm';`
   - Replace line 199:
     ```tsx
     <div className="detail-body">{issue.body}</div>
     ```
     with:
     ```tsx
     <div className="detail-body markdown-body">
       <Markdown remarkPlugins={[remarkGfm]}>{issue.body}</Markdown>
     </div>
     ```
   - The `markdown-body` class will be the shared class for all markdown-rendered content.

2. **Update `apps/desktop/src/components/detail/DetailPanel.css`:**
   - In the `.detail-body` rule, **remove** `white-space: pre-wrap;` -- this conflicts with markdown rendering (it would prevent proper paragraph/list layout). The markdown renderer handles whitespace via its own block elements.
   - Keep all other `.detail-body` styles (padding, background, border, font-size, line-height, color, word-break, max-height, overflow-y).

3. **Create `apps/desktop/src/components/detail/markdown.css`:**
   - Define shared markdown styles under the `.markdown-body` class:
     ```css
     .markdown-body p { margin: 0 0 8px 0; }
     .markdown-body p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
     .markdown-body code { background: rgba(0,0,0,0.3); padding: 2px 5px; border-radius: 3px; font-size: 0.9em; font-family: 'Consolas', 'Courier New', monospace; }
     .markdown-body pre { background: rgba(0,0,0,0.3); padding: 10px; border-radius: 4px; overflow-x: auto; margin: 8px 0; }
     .markdown-body pre code { background: none; padding: 0; }
     .markdown-body a { color: #58a6ff; text-decoration: none; }
     .markdown-body a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
     .markdown-body ul, .markdown-body ol { margin: 8px 0; padding-left: 20px; }
     .markdown-body blockquote { border-left: 3px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.15); margin: 8px 0; padding-left: 12px; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.5); }
     .markdown-body img { max-width: 100%; border-radius: 4px; }
     .markdown-body h1, .markdown-body h2, .markdown-body h3, .markdown-body h4 { margin: 12px 0 6px 0; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.85); }
     .markdown-body h1 { font-size: 1.2em; }
     .markdown-body h2 { font-size: 1.1em; }
     .markdown-body h3 { font-size: 1em; }
     ```
   - Add GFM-specific styles:
     ```css
     /* Tables */
     .markdown-body table { border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; margin: 8px 0; }
     .markdown-body th, .markdown-body td { border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: 6px 10px; font-size: 12px; text-align: left; }
     .markdown-body th { background: rgba(255,255,255,0.05); color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); font-weight: 600; }
     .markdown-body td { color: rgba(255,255,255,0.7); }
     /* Strikethrough */
     .markdown-body del { color: rgba(255,255,255,0.4); }
     /* Task lists */
     .markdown-body input[type='checkbox'] { margin-right: 6px; }
     .markdown-body li { margin: 2px 0; }
     /* Horizontal rules */
     .markdown-body hr { border: none; border-top: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1); margin: 12px 0; }
     ```

4. **Update `apps/desktop/src/components/detail/IssueComments.tsx`:**
   - Add import: `import './markdown.css';`
   - Update the comment body div (line 129) to include the shared class:
     ```tsx
     <div className="comment-body markdown-body">
     ```

5. **Update `apps/desktop/src/components/detail/IssueComments.css`:**
   - Remove ALL the `.comment-body` markdown element styles (lines 51-117: p, code, pre, a, ul/ol, blockquote, img, h1-h3) since they are now covered by `markdown.css` under `.markdown-body`.
   - Keep the `.comment-body` base styles (color, line-height, font-size on lines 45-49) since those set the comment-specific base font.

6. **Import `markdown.css` in `IssueDetail.tsx`:**
   - Add `import './markdown.css';` at the top of IssueDetail.tsx.

This phase makes markdown render in both the issue body and comments with consistent styling, using GFM for tables, task lists, strikethrough, and autolinks. XSS is handled by react-markdown's default behavior of not rendering raw HTML.

Install and configure a lightweight syntax highlighter for fenced code blocks in markdown-rendered content.

Steps:

1. **Install rehype-highlight and highlight.js:**
   - Run from `apps/desktop`: `pnpm add rehype-highlight highlight.js`
   - `rehype-highlight` is a rehype plugin that integrates with react-markdown via the `rehypePlugins` prop. It uses highlight.js under the hood for language detection and tokenization.
   - This is lighter than react-syntax-highlighter and integrates directly with the react-markdown plugin pipeline.

2. **Create a shared MarkdownRenderer component at `apps/desktop/src/components/detail/MarkdownRenderer.tsx`:**
   - This component encapsulates the Markdown + plugins configuration so it is consistent everywhere:
     ```tsx
     import Markdown from 'react-markdown';
     import remarkGfm from 'remark-gfm';
     import rehypeHighlight from 'rehype-highlight';
     import 'highlight.js/styles/github-dark.css';

     interface MarkdownRendererProps {
       children: string;
     }

     export function MarkdownRenderer({ children }: MarkdownRendererProps) {
       return (
         <Markdown
           remarkPlugins={[remarkGfm]}
           rehypePlugins={[rehypeHighlight]}
         >
           {children}
         </Markdown>
       );
     }
     ```
   - Import the `github-dark` highlight.js theme CSS, which looks good in a dark UI. If it clashes, alternatives include `github-dark-dimmed`, `atom-one-dark`, or `vs2015`.

3. **Update `apps/desktop/src/components/detail/IssueDetail.tsx`:**
   - Replace `import Markdown from 'react-markdown';` and `import remarkGfm from 'remark-gfm';` with `import { MarkdownRenderer } from './MarkdownRenderer';`
   - Replace the `<Markdown remarkPlugins={[remarkGfm]}>` usage with `<MarkdownRenderer>`:
     ```tsx
     <div className="detail-body markdown-body">
       <MarkdownRenderer>{issue.body}</MarkdownRenderer>
     </div>
     ```

4. **Update `apps/desktop/src/components/detail/IssueComments.tsx`:**
   - Replace `import Markdown from 'react-markdown';` and `import remarkGfm from 'remark-gfm';` with `import { MarkdownRenderer } from './MarkdownRenderer';`
   - Replace the `<Markdown remarkPlugins={[remarkGfm]}>` usage with `<MarkdownRenderer>`:
     ```tsx
     <div className="comment-body markdown-body">
       <MarkdownRenderer>{comment.body}</MarkdownRenderer>
     </div>
     ```

5. **Verify the highlight.js CSS does not conflict with existing styles:**
   - The `github-dark.css` theme applies styles to `.hljs` classes inside `<code>` elements. Since our `.markdown-body pre code` resets background to `none`, we may need to ensure the hljs background takes precedence. Add to `markdown.css` if needed:
     ```css
     .markdown-body pre code.hljs { background: transparent; }
     ```

This approach keeps syntax highlighting lightweight (only imports the CSS theme + auto-detection, no per-language bundles by default) and centralizes the markdown configuration in one component.

Ensure all clickable links in rendered markdown open in the user's default OS browser rather than navigating the Tauri webview.

Steps:

1. **Update `apps/desktop/src/components/detail/MarkdownRenderer.tsx`:**
   - Add a custom `components` prop to the `<Markdown>` element to override the default `<a>` tag behavior:
     ```tsx
     import { open } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-shell';
     // OR if plugin-shell is not available, use window.__TAURI__

     const components = {
       a: ({ href, children, ...props }: React.AnchorHTMLAttributes<HTMLAnchorElement>) => (
         <a
           {...props}
           href={href}
           onClick={(e) => {
             e.preventDefault();
             if (href) {
               window.open(href, '_blank');
             }
           }}
         >
           {children}
         </a>
       ),
     };
     ```
   - Pass `components={components}` to the `<Markdown>` element.
   - Note: The app already uses `window.open(url, '_blank')` in IssueDetail.tsx (line 49) and ReleaseDetail.tsx (line 26) for opening GitHub URLs. This is the established pattern in the codebase. If Tauri blocks `window.open`, the fallback is to use the Tauri shell plugin (`@tauri-apps/plugin-shell`'s `open()` function), but that plugin is NOT currently in the npm dependencies. Since `window.open` is already used and presumably working, use that pattern first.
   - If `window.open` does not work for in-content links (Tauri may treat them differently than programmatic calls), install the shell plugin:
     - Add `@tauri-apps/plugin-shell` to devDependencies in `apps/desktop/package.json`
     - Add `tauri-plugin-shell` to `apps/desktop/src-tauri/Cargo.toml` dependencies
     - Register in `apps/desktop/src-tauri/src/lib.rs` plugin builder
     - Use `import { open } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-shell'; open(href);`

2. **Also add `target="_blank"` and `rel="noopener noreferrer"` to links** as a safety fallback in the custom `a` component.

3. **Verify image rendering:**
   - GitHub issue images are typically hosted at `https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/...` or `https://github.com/user-attachments/...`
   - react-markdown renders `<img>` tags by default, and the `.markdown-body img { max-width: 100% }` CSS handles sizing.
   - Tauri's webview should load external images by default (CSP is set to `null` in tauri.conf.json, meaning no restrictions).
   - No additional work is needed for images unless CSP issues arise.

This phase ensures that clicking any link in the markdown-rendered issue body or comments opens the URL externally, which is the expected behavior for a desktop app.
